│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs inside                             │
│ VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe::computeCost when it attempts to cast a Type* │
│ to VectorType via cast<VectorType>(VectorTy). The assertion fails because     │
│ VectorTy is not a VectorType; it is a scalar type when VF == 1. The cost      │
│ model path is using a shuffle cost (SK_Splice) which requires a vector type,  │
│ but the code doesn’t guard against the scalar VF case.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's  │
│ Log:\nThe opt output shows the crash in computeCost with VF values leading to │
│ mask construction and a call to getShuffleCost using a VectorType cast. The   │
│ Scalar Evolution analysis indicates fixed trip counts and nothing unusual     │
│ that would force vectorization. The earlier check only handles scalable VF    │
│ with known min value of 1. In our reproducer, VF is likely a fixed            │
│ (non-scalable) 1, leading to VectorTy being scalar from ToVectorTy(..., VF)   │
│ and the subsequent cast failing.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn               │
│ VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe::computeCost, the logic constructs a mask and │
│ infers a vector type using ToVectorTy(..., VF). For VF == 1 (fixed scalar),   │
│ ToVectorTy returns the scalar type. The function then unconditionally calls   │
│ TTI.getShuffleCost with cast<VectorType>(VectorTy), causing an assertion      │
│ failure. The code only guards the scalable VF==1 case, but misses the fixed   │
│ VF==1 case. Therefore, the root cause is a missing guard for VF.isScalar()    │
│ (i.e., VF == 1 fixed) before using vector-only cost computations.\n\n4.       │
│ Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit Point:                                          │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp:3318-3332.\nChange             │
│ VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe::computeCost to early-return for any scalar   │
│ VF, not just the scalable VF==1 case. Also, construct the mask and invoke     │
│ getShuffleCost only when VF.isVector().\n\nSuggested patch (conceptual):\n-   │
│ Add: if (VF.isScalar()) return InstructionCost::getInvalid();\n- Keep         │
│ existing scalable guard or unify it with the scalar guard.\n- Ensure we only  │
│ build Mask and call getShuffleCost when VectorTy is a                         │
│ VectorType.\n\nConcretely, replace:\n  if (VF.isScalable() &&                 │
│ VF.getKnownMinValue() == 1)\n    return InstructionCost::getInvalid();\n      │
│ SmallVector<int> Mask(VF.getKnownMinValue());\n  std::iota(Mask.begin(),      │
│ Mask.end(), VF.getKnownMinValue() - 1);\n  Type *VectorTy = ToVectorTy(...,   │
│ VF);\n  return Ctx.TTI.getShuffleCost(..., cast<VectorType>(VectorTy), Mask,  │
│ ..., ...);\nwith:\n  if (VF.isScalar() || (VF.isScalable() &&                 │
│ VF.getKnownMinValue() == 1))\n    return InstructionCost::getInvalid();\n     │
│ SmallVector<int> Mask(VF.getKnownMinValue());\n  std::iota(Mask.begin(),      │
│ Mask.end(), VF.getKnownMinValue() - 1);\n  Type *VectorTy = ToVectorTy(...,   │
│ VF);\n  assert(isa<VectorType>(VectorTy) && \"Expected vector type for FOR    │
│ cost\");\n  return Ctx.TTI.getShuffleCost(..., cast<VectorType>(VectorTy),    │
│ Mask, ..., ...);\n\nThis ensures we never attempt a vector shuffle cost for   │
│ scalar VF.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is due to requesting a vector shuffle │
│ cost with VF==1 (fixed scalar), leading to a cast of a scalar Type* to        │
│ VectorType*. Adding an early return for VF.isScalar(), alongside the existing │
│ scalable VF==1 guard, prevents the erroneous path and aligns the cost         │
│ computation with valid vectorization scenarios. This fix avoids the assertion │
│ and keeps the cost model well-defined for the first-order recurrence PHIs."}) │
