│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs inside VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe::computeCost when it  │
│ attempts to cast a Type* to VectorType via cast<VectorType>(VectorTy). The    │
│ assertion fails because VectorTy is not a VectorType; it is a scalar type     │
│ when VF == 1. The cost model path is using a shuffle cost (SK_Splice) which   │
│ requires a vector type, but the code doesn’t guard against the scalar VF      │
│ case.                                                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The opt output shows the crash in computeCost with VF values leading to mask  │
│ construction and a call to getShuffleCost using a VectorType cast. The Scalar │
│ Evolution analysis indicates fixed trip counts and nothing unusual that would │
│ force vectorization. The earlier check only handles scalable VF with known    │
│ min value of 1. In our reproducer, VF is likely a fixed (non-scalable) 1,     │
│ leading to VectorTy being scalar from ToVectorTy(..., VF) and the subsequent  │
│ cast failing.                                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe::computeCost, the logic constructs a mask  │
│ and infers a vector type using ToVectorTy(..., VF). For VF == 1 (fixed        │
│ scalar), ToVectorTy returns the scalar type. The function then                │
│ unconditionally calls TTI.getShuffleCost with cast<VectorType>(VectorTy),     │
│ causing an assertion failure. The code only guards the scalable VF==1 case,   │
│ but misses the fixed VF==1 case. Therefore, the root cause is a missing guard │
│ for VF.isScalar() (i.e., VF == 1 fixed) before using vector-only cost         │
│ computations.                                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Edit Point: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp:3318-3332.         │
│ Change VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe::computeCost to early-return for any   │
│ scalar VF, not just the scalable VF==1 case. Also, construct the mask and     │
│ invoke getShuffleCost only when VF.isVector().                                │
│                                                                               │
│ Suggested patch (conceptual):                                                 │
│ - Add: if (VF.isScalar()) return InstructionCost::getInvalid();               │
│ - Keep existing scalable guard or unify it with the scalar guard.             │
│ - Ensure we only build Mask and call getShuffleCost when VectorTy is a        │
│ VectorType.                                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ Concretely, replace:                                                          │
│   if (VF.isScalable() && VF.getKnownMinValue() == 1)                          │
│     return InstructionCost::getInvalid();                                     │
│   SmallVector<int> Mask(VF.getKnownMinValue());                               │
│   std::iota(Mask.begin(), Mask.end(), VF.getKnownMinValue() - 1);             │
│   Type *VectorTy = ToVectorTy(..., VF);                                       │
│   return Ctx.TTI.getShuffleCost(..., cast<VectorType>(VectorTy), Mask, ...,   │
│ ...);                                                                         │
│ with:                                                                         │
│   if (VF.isScalar() || (VF.isScalable() && VF.getKnownMinValue() == 1))       │
│     return InstructionCost::getInvalid();                                     │
│   SmallVector<int> Mask(VF.getKnownMinValue());                               │
│   std::iota(Mask.begin(), Mask.end(), VF.getKnownMinValue() - 1);             │
│   Type *VectorTy = ToVectorTy(..., VF);                                       │
│   assert(isa<VectorType>(VectorTy) && "Expected vector type for FOR cost");   │
│   return Ctx.TTI.getShuffleCost(..., cast<VectorType>(VectorTy), Mask, ...,   │
│ ...);                                                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ This ensures we never attempt a vector shuffle cost for scalar VF.            │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash is due to requesting a vector shuffle cost with VF==1 (fixed        │
│ scalar), leading to a cast of a scalar Type* to VectorType*. Adding an early  │
│ return for VF.isScalar(), alongside the existing scalable VF==1 guard,        │
│ prevents the erroneous path and aligns the cost computation with valid        │
│ vectorization scenarios. This fix avoids the assertion and keeps the cost     │
│ model well-defined for the first-order recurrence PHIs.                       │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
